1. Lossless Compression
No information is lost.
Original data can be perfectly reconstructed.

Used in:
Medical imaging
Archival systems
Scientific imaging
Text/data storage

Techniques
| Method                    | Principle                      |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Run Length Encoding (RLE) | Repeated symbol coding         |
| Huffman Coding            | Variable-length entropy coding |
| Arithmetic Coding         | Probability-based coding       |
| LZW                       | Dictionary-based coding        |
| Predictive Coding         | Encode prediction error        |

Examples
| Media Type | Formats    |
| ---------- | ---------- |
| Images     | PNG, TIFF  |
| Audio      | FLAC, ALAC |
| Video      | FFV1       |

2. Lossy Compression
Some information is discarded.

Goal:
Large compression ratio
Acceptable visual/audio quality

Used in:
Streaming
Broadcasting
OTT
Gaming

Taxonomy by Media Type
A. Image Compression
Image Compression Taxonomy
Image Compression
│
├── Lossless
│
└── Lossy
      │
      ├── Transform Coding
      ├── Predictive Coding
      ├── Vector Quantization
      ├── Fractal Coding
      └── Neural Compression
A1. Transform Coding
Most important category.
Transforms image into frequency domain.

Techniques:
DCT
Wavelet
Fourier

Examples:
JPEG
JPEG2000

A2. Predictive Coding
Predict current pixel from neighboring pixels.
Examples:
DPCM
JPEG-LS

A3. Vector Quantization (VQ)
Image blocks mapped to codebooks.

Advantages:
High compression

Disadvantages:
Codebook complexity

A4. Fractal Compression
Uses self-similarity in images.
Rarely used commercially due to:
High encoding complexity

A5. Neural Image Compression
Deep learning-based compression:
Autoencoders
Hyperpriors
Transformers

B. Audio Compression
Taxonomy
Audio Compression
│
├── Waveform Coding
├── Parametric Coding
├── Perceptual Coding
